'''Carlotism''' was a political movement that took place in the [[Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata]] between 1808 and 1812; it intended to make [[Carlota Joaquina of Spain|Carlota Joaquina]], [[Infanta]] of Spain and [[List of Portuguese consorts|Queen Consort of Portugal]], its monarch.

After [[Napoleon's invasion of Spain]], [[Fernando VII]], Carlota's younger brother, was forced to abdicate and give the throne to [[Joseph Bonaparte]]. Most Spanish did not consider him a legitimate king and Carlota, an ambitious woman, seemed like a possible option to keep the royal line safe. 

Carlota was living in [[Brazil]] by then, after the nobility of [[Portugal]] moved from Portugal to the Americas because of [[Napoleón's invasion of Portugal]]. 

Carlotism found strong resistance from many parties involved: the viceroys, other Spanish authorities in the Americas, part of the [[Criollo people|Criollos]], and the British. The plans were never applied, and supporters of it would later turn to independence.

