{{EngvarB|date=June 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} The '''Rooney Prize for Irish Literature''' was created in 1976 by the Irish American businessman [[Dan Rooney]], owner and chairman of the [[NFL]] [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] franchise and former [[United States Ambassador to Ireland|US Ambassador to Ireland]].<ref name=irish_tales_have_rooney_angle/> The prize is awarded to [[Irish literature|Irish writers]] aged under 40 who are published in Irish or English. Although often associated with individual books, it is intended to reward a body of work. Originally worth £750,<ref name="Diary">"An Irishman's Diary", ''The Irish Times'', 7 May 1976.</ref> the current value of the prize is €10,000.<ref name="Walsh">Caroline Walsh, "Loose Leaves", ''The Irish Times'', 21 June 2008.</ref>
